  "points": [
    {
      "title": "Independent pronouns (ni, kai, ke…)",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Say who you mean",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 1,
      "explanation": "The free pronouns are ni (I), kai (you, m), ke (you, f), shi (he), ita (she), mu (we), ku (you all), su (they). Hausa marks gender in the second and third person singular — kai to a man, ke to a woman.",
      "culture_note": "",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Hausa language — grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hausa_language#Grammar"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} malami ne.",
          "answer": "Ni",
          "translation": "I am a teacher.",
          "hint": "the 'I' pronoun",
          "display_order": 1
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} tana nan.",
          "answer": "Ita",
          "translation": "She is here.",
          "hint": "the 'she' pronoun",
          "display_order": 2
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Identity with ne / ce",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Say what someone or something is",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 2,
      "explanation": "Identity sentences end in ne (masculine/plural) or ce (feminine): Ni malami ne (I am a teacher), Ita malama ce (She is a teacher), Su ɗalibai ne (They are students). The particle agrees with the SUBJECT noun's gender.",
      "culture_note": "Hausa has two genders, masculine and feminine — most feminines end in -a, and ne/ce is your first meeting with that system.",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Hausa language — grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hausa_language#Grammar"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
        {
          "sentence": "Ni malami {{answer}}.",
          "answer": "ne",
          "translation": "I am a (male) teacher.",
          "hint": "masculine particle",
          "display_order": 1
        },
        {
          "sentence": "Ita malama {{answer}}.",
          "answer": "ce",
          "translation": "She is a (female) teacher.",
          "hint": "feminine particle",
          "display_order": 2
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Completive aspect (na, ka, ya, ta…)",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Say what happened (done and finished)",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 3,
      "explanation": "Hausa conjugates with aspect pronouns before the verb. Completive (did/has done): na (I), ka/kin (you m/f), ya (he), ta (she), mun (we), kun (you all), sun (they): Na ci abinci (I ate food), Sun tafi (They left).",
      "culture_note": "",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Hausa language — grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hausa_language#Grammar"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} ci abinci.",
          "answer": "Na",
          "translation": "I ate food.",
          "hint": "completive 'I'",
          "display_order": 1
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} tafi kasuwa.",
          "answer": "Ta",
          "translation": "She went to the market.",
          "hint": "completive 'she'",
          "display_order": 2
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Continuous aspect (ina, kana, yana…)",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Say what is happening",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 4,
      "explanation": "The continuous uses -na pronouns plus the verbal noun: Ina cin abinci (I am eating), Yana aiki (He is working), Muna zuwa (We are coming). Ina also opens 'where' questions: Ina kake? (Where are you?).",
      "culture_note": "",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Hausa language — grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hausa_language#Grammar"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} cin abinci.",
          "answer": "Ina",
          "translation": "I am eating food.",
          "hint": "continuous 'I'",
          "display_order": 1
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} aiki yanzu.",
          "answer": "Yana",
          "translation": "He is working now.",
          "hint": "continuous 'he'",
          "display_order": 2
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Future with zan, za ka…",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Say what will happen",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 5,
      "explanation": "The future combines za with the person: zan (I will), za ka/za ki, zai (he), za ta, za mu, za ku, za su: Zan tafi gida (I will go home), Za ta dawo gobe (She will return tomorrow).",
      "culture_note": "",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Hausa language — grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hausa_language#Grammar"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} tafi gida.",
          "answer": "Zan",
          "translation": "I will go home.",
          "hint": "future 'I'",
          "display_order": 1
        },
        {
          "sentence": "Za {{answer}} dawo gobe.",
          "answer": "ta",
          "translation": "She will return tomorrow.",
          "hint": "future 'she'",
          "display_order": 2
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Existence: akwai / babu",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Say what there is and isn't",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 6,
      "explanation": "Akwai asserts existence, babu denies it: Akwai ruwa (There is water), Babu kuɗi (There is no money). With 'have' meaning: Akwai littafi a wurina (I have a book — lit. there's a book at my place); everyday 'have' also uses da: Ina da mota (I have a car).",
      "culture_note": "",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Hausa language — grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hausa_language#Grammar"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} ruwa a gida.",
          "answer": "Akwai",
          "translation": "There is water at home.",
          "hint": "'there is'",
          "display_order": 1
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} kuɗi.",
          "answer": "Babu",
          "translation": "There is no money.",
          "hint": "'there is not'",
          "display_order": 2
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Negation ba … ba",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Deny statements",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 7,
      "explanation": "Most negation wraps the clause in ba … ba: Ban ci ba (I didn't eat — ba+na fuses to ban), Ba ta zo ba (She didn't come). The continuous negates with bā (single): Ba na zuwa (I am not coming/going).",
      "culture_note": "",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Hausa language — grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hausa_language#Grammar"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} ci abinci ba.",
          "answer": "Ban",
          "translation": "I did not eat food.",
          "hint": "ba + na fused, first half",
          "display_order": 1
        },
        {
          "sentence": "Ba ta zo {{answer}}.",
          "answer": "ba",
          "translation": "She did not come.",
          "hint": "the closing ba",
          "display_order": 2
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The genitive linker -n / -r",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Link 'X of Y' and possession",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 8,
      "explanation": "Possession links nouns with -n (masculine/plural) or -r (feminine): littafin Audu (Audu's book, littafi+n), motar Audu (Audu's car, mota+r), gidan malami (the teacher's house). The linker matches the FIRST noun's gender.",
      "culture_note": "",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Hausa language — grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hausa_language#Grammar"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} Audu yana nan.",
          "answer": "Littafin",
          "translation": "Audu's book is here.",
          "hint": "littafi + -n (masculine)",
          "display_order": 1
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} Audu sabuwa ce.",
          "answer": "Motar",
          "translation": "Audu's car is new.",
          "hint": "mota + -r (feminine)",
          "display_order": 2
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Questions (me, wa, ina)",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Ask what, who, and where",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 9,
      "explanation": "Me (what), wa (who), ina (where), yaushe (when), nawa (how much): Me ka ci? (What did you eat?), Wa ya zo? (Who came?), Ina kake? (Where are you?). Yes/no questions add ko…? or just rising intonation: Ka ci abinci? / Ko ka ci?",
      "culture_note": "",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Hausa language — grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hausa_language#Grammar"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} ka ci?",
          "answer": "Me",
          "translation": "What did you eat?",
          "hint": "'what'",
          "display_order": 1
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} ya zo?",
          "answer": "Wa",
          "translation": "Who came?",
          "hint": "'who'",
          "display_order": 2
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Common plurals",
      "level": "A2",
      "function": "Name many things",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 1,
      "explanation": "Hausa plurals change the word's shape, often with -oCi or internal -a-: mota → motoci (cars), littafi → littattafai (books), gida → gidaje (houses), yaro → yara (children). Each noun's plural is learned with it — patterns help but don't fully predict.",
      "culture_note": "",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Hausa language — grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hausa_language#Grammar"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
        {
          "sentence": "Ina da {{answer}} biyu.",
          "answer": "motoci",
          "translation": "I have two cars.",
          "hint": "plural of mota",
          "display_order": 1
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} suna wasa.",
          "answer": "Yara",
          "translation": "The children are playing.",
          "hint": "plural of yaro",
          "display_order": 2
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Object pronouns",
      "level": "A2",
      "function": "Say who receives the action",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 2,
      "explanation": "After the verb: ni (me), ka/ki (you m/f), shi (him), ta (her), mu (us), ku (you all), su (them): Na gan shi (I saw him), Sun ji mu (They heard us). Many verbs shorten before an object: gani → gan (see).",
      "culture_note": "",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Hausa language — grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hausa_language#Grammar"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
        {
          "sentence": "Na gan {{answer}} a kasuwa.",
          "answer": "shi",
          "translation": "I saw him at the market.",
          "hint": "'him' after the verb",
          "display_order": 1
        },
        {
          "sentence": "Sun ji {{answer}}.",
          "answer": "mu",
          "translation": "They heard us.",
          "hint": "'us' after the verb",
          "display_order": 2
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Possessive pronouns (-na, -nka…)",
      "level": "A2",
      "function": "Say whose things are",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 3,
      "explanation": "Possessives attach through the linker: littafina (my book), littafinka/ki (your, m/f owner), littafinsa (his), littafinta (her); feminine nouns use -r-: motata (my car), motarsa (his car). Gender of the THING picks -n-/-r-; the ending shows the owner.",
      "culture_note": "",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Hausa language — grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hausa_language#Grammar"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
